snippet.title: It Happened in Barcelona - Windows Weekly 610
snippet.description:
HoloLens 2 Hands-On, Build 2019
HoloLens 2 at MWC

--  As expected, Microsoft announces HoloLens 2 at MWC 2019. Paul goes hands-on.
--  Mary Jo says it's all about the cloud. Azure Remote Rendering, Azure Spatial Anchors, Dynamics 365 apps and subscription pricing.
--  Paul sees how it fits perfectly into the new Microsoft under Satya Nadella, hitting all of the AACO ("Accessibility, AI, Cloud, and Open") bullet-points that products need to survive there.
--  Accessibility - This one is a bit light, but it's more accessible in the sense that it can more easily be used by anyone and without training or complex setup
--  AI - Poster-child for Microsoft's AI prowess
--  Cloud - HoloLens 2 won't ever be a direct money maker, instead, it's a supporting piece for Microsoft's cloud subscriptions
--  Open: Open stores, open app support (including Firefox). Even anti-Microsoft veteran Tim Sweeney is on board, and he's insane. (What do we make of Microsoft's comments about "an open store" for HoloLens?)
--  Inside scoop: Sources have confirmed that Microsoft had no idea what developers would do with HoloLens. But the market has spoken, and the games focus we saw during the 1.0 announcements were nowhere to be seen for v2.
--  One more thing: Oh, Microsoft also announced Azure Kinect because it uses some of the same elements as HL2.
All the Rest

--  Build 2019 registration is open. Mixed reality is on the agenda (but no mention of Windows/Microsoft 365)
--  Lite, Centaurus, Pegasus, Santorini, oh my: There was nothing announced at MWC, but Microsoft's post-Windows client future is becoming clearer every day.
--  There were two more Windows 10 Insider Preview builds this past week • Chromium-based Edge preview should be coming soon.

The Division 2 from Ubisoft is finally here. To celebrate the release of this post-apocalyptic loot shooter, we put together a PC designed for the Strategic Homeland Division.
This... is the Dark Base Division gaming PC. But before we show off the finished build, here’s how it all came together.
The Dark Base 700 White Edition case by be quiet! was where we started. This color is a limited edition, but the white and orange accents and customizable interior were exactly what we were looking for.

The Dark Base 700 comes with three Silent Wings 140 millimeter fans already installed, modular options, and plenty of great cable routing choices. But that was before the Dark Base was recruited into The Division. Now, it’s a totally different animal.

This SHD Phoenix Logo was made from a custom, hand cut stencil. After the logo and lettering stencils were placed on the case, a layer of acrylic paint was applied.

The outside looks like its seen battle, but the inside of this build tells another story. These Riing Trio fans from Thermaltake bring to mind ISAC, the intelligent System Analytic Computer that assists agents in the field. The glowing rings represent the shoulder-mounted ISAC units worn by the elite SHD agents of The Division. 

Running this beautiful gaming PC is an Intel Core i5-9600K CPU in a ASUS PRIME Z370-A II motherboard. The K designation means this 9th Gen processor is overclockable, so a powerful cooler is important. 

We went with be quiet! for the CPU cooler as well, and decided on the Dark Rock 4. The Silent Wings 135 millimeter fan makes almost no audible sound, and the high cooling performance via six copper heat pipes ensure the CPU will run nice and cool, even when under a heavy load.

The Division 2 is a beautiful game, and to make sure we took advantage of that, we decided on an unusual GPU from EVGA.
This is the EVGA GeForce RTX 2060 XC BLACK. It’s a bit on the small and thick side, as EVGA wanted to provide options for those of you with horizontal clearance issues. This 2.75 slot graphics card uses a taller fan hub and a larger heat sink, paired with a single fan to keep that RTX chip nice and cool, despite the smaller horizontal surface area.

Between the be quiet! case mods and the detailed lighting, the Dark Base Division is a perfect PC for experiencing The Division 2. Check the links below if you want to put together your own Division inspired build, and feel free to share in the comments.

And speaking of keeping cool, that brings us up to...let's see...eight fans in total? That's what we like to see. 

We finished off the build with an Intel M.2 SSD for storage, alongside 32GB of RAM and an 850 watt power supply, both from Corsair.

The darkFlash i5 Phantom is more than just a lightshow. It looks great, runs cool, and is an all-around fantastic addition to our lineup of beautiful gaming PCs.

snippet.title: Apple's Streaming Service: What to Expect
snippet.description:
Can Apple actually take on Netflix, Hulu and Amazon in the increasingly crowded world of streaming video? We're about to find out on March 25th, when Apple is expected to give us a glimpse at its long-awaited video service. It's something the company has been building out in the open over the past few years, so it's not exactly a secret. After high profile flops like Planet of the Apps and Carpool Karaoke, it's a bit tough to feel that excited about whatever Apple is cooking up -- but there's always the chance that it could offer something truly unique.

snippet.title: Apple refreshes iMacs with new chips
snippet.description:
It's shaping up to be a busy week for Apple. Yesterday the company unveiled two updated iPads, and today it announced the iMac is getting a minor refresh. Going forward, the 21.5-inch model will be offered with an eighth-gen six-core Intel Core i5 CPU at the high end, plus 4GB AMD Radeon Pro Vega 20 graphics. That top-tier sku will also include an eighth-gen six-core Core i7 processor as a configure-to-order option. At the entry-level, the 21.5-inch model starts with a dual-core seventh-generation Core i5 processor, and then moves up to configurations with eighth-gen quad-core chips.
